<tr><td></td><td>LOCATION--Ops</td></tr>
<tr id="L39"><td><a href="#L39">39</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: There is a diagram of a baseball field on the big table. Kira is reading aloud from a PADD, and Worf and Nog each have their own.</td></tr>

<tr id="L40"><td><a href="#L40">40</a></td><td>KIRA:  Chapter twenty five. The infield fly rule is invoked in instances where, with both first base and second base occupied, or with first, second and third base occupied</td></tr>

<tr id="L41"><td><a href="#L41">41</a></td><td>WORF:  What if there is a runner at home?</td></tr>

<tr id="L42"><td><a href="#L42">42</a></td><td>NOG:  There's never a runner at home.</td></tr>

<tr id="L43"><td><a href="#L43">43</a></td><td>KIRA:  Okay. And fewer than two outs, the batter hits a high fly.</td></tr>

<tr id="L44"><td><a href="#L44">44</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: Worf looks it up on his PADD.</td></tr>

<tr id="L45"><td><a href="#L45">45</a></td><td>WORF:  Fly. The term for a batted ball while it is in the air.</td></tr>

<tr id="L46"><td><a href="#L46">46</a></td><td>KIRA:  Oh, right. Er, fewer than two out, the batter hits a high fly which in the judgment of the umpire can readily be caught by an infielder or the pitcher or catcher inside fair ground. The batter is then called out regardless of whether the ball is subsequently caught or not.</td></tr>

<tr id="L47"><td><a href="#L47">47</a></td><td>NOG:  That seems simple enough.</td></tr>

<tr id="L48"><td><a href="#L48">48</a></td><td>KIRA:  An attempt to bunt, however, under the conditions noted above, which results in a fair fly shall not be regarded an infield fly. What's a bunt?</td></tr>

<tr><td></td><td>LOCATION--Quark's</td></tr>
<tr id="L49"><td><a href="#L49">49</a></td><td>BASHIR:  A bunt. A ball which has been deliberately tapped into the area between the pitcher and the catcher by the batter in order to force the fielding side to throw out the batter and allow a runner to advance.</td></tr>

<tr id="L50"><td><a href="#L50">50</a></td><td>EZRI:  (with the PADD) Right. Chief, what's a grand slam?</td></tr>

